On September 30, 1928, exactly 90 years ago, the British bacteriologist Alexander Fleming announced an unprecedented discovery.
The discovery of penicillin marked the beginning of the era of modern antibiotics, brought Fleming worldwide fame and made him a Nobel laureate.
By the way, the release of penicillin from mold fungi was not the first discovery of Fleming.
A few years earlier, when caught cold, he had planted mucus from his own nose on a petri cup (a glass lid in which bacteria were tested) and a few days later discovered that the bacteria there had been destroyed.
He discovered penicillin almost by accident.
