Kosachev: At the 73rd session of the UN General Assembly the topic of Russia in a negative way was almost absent
Head of the Federation Council Committee on Foreign Affairs Konstantin Kosachev considers the 73rd session of the UN General Assembly successful for Russia and does not exclude that it can become a turning point in the perception of Russia as an integral participant in solving global problems.
"The uniqueness of this 73rd session, in my opinion, lies in the fact that the rhetoric to which we are almost accustomed in recent years against Russia, was now much more muted", - said the senator in an interview published on Sunday",Rossiyskaya Gazeta".
He explained that in previous years, the Russian Federation was sometimes "identified as one of the three main threats to humanity, now along with Ebola, now along with climate change or terrorism, Russia was in this row, at least in the statement of a group of Western countries, which spoke quite unanimously on this subject".
At the 73rd session, Kosachev stressed",the topic of Russia in a negative way was virtually absent".
"If we carefully analyze the speech of the President of the United States, the President of France, the speech of the Minister of Foreign Affairs of Germany, I do not take Ukraine, Georgia, or the British, at least, the choir was not quite accurate", - said the politician, noting that Russia "was no longer a wall, which trains blows with a tennis ball".
The head of the relevant committee of the Security Council does not rule out that this indicates a certain trend, which, in his opinion",will allocate the current session [of the UN General Assembly], although this trend may be fully manifested in a year, two, three".
"I do not rule out that the current session in some sense may be a turning point", - admitted Kosachev, explaining that "too many examples of how with the involvement of Russia managed to move forward in international affairs".
He cited the situation in Syria, Iran and North Korea as examples.
"So far, unfortunately, it is not Ukraine, but I have no doubt that the Russian vision of the Ukrainian crisis will also be in demand over time", - added the parliamentarian.
This is due to the fact, he believes, that there is "an adequate, sound perception of Russia as not just a possible - an integral participant in solving the global problems of our time".
"I would not like to make a mistake, but I have a feeling that somewhere we pass a point beyond which the movement will no longer be a reverse, it will be a movement forward", - he added.
Kosachev called another "interesting and important feeling" in this context "the request for a Russian vision of how the modern world should develop".
"I attended many meetings of the head of the Russian delegation [at the session of the General Assembly], Foreign Minister Sergey Lavrov, I held my own meetings, and I saw with great pleasure that if a year or two or five years ago the Russian opinion, the Russian vision of what is happening in the world, in general, no one was interested, but now the situation is different", - said the chairman of the Security Council Committee.
According to him, this is due to the fact that "the so-called new liberal order, which is represented by the West, has no answers to the questions of how to solve world problems due to the obvious shortage of ideas in the global space, lack of ideas on how to solve the problems of the Middle East, terrorism, nuclear non-proliferation, migration".
"And here the demand for the Russian vision becomes more and more obvious", Kosachev expressed confidence, stressing that in this sense he considers "the current session successful for the work of the Russian delegation, successful for Russia".
