The term of death of the universe is named
The universe will last another 140 billion years, ten times the age of the observed world of about 13.8 billion years.
Research of an international team of scientists posted in the library of electronic preprints arXiv.org and aimed at publication in the journal Publications of the Astronomical Society of Japan, the Japanese newspaper Asahi Shimbun.
Experts came to such conclusions by observing about ten million galaxies with the help of the HSC (Hyper Suprime-Cam) camera of the Subaru telescope.
By tracking the distribution of dark matter and dark energy, which account for more than 95 percent of the mass energy of the observed world, scientists, working within the standard cosmological model "Cold Dark Matter" ("Cold Dark Matter"), estimated the rate of expansion of the universe, which was a little slower than previously thought.
The press release of the Subaru Observatory noted that the observations provided a detailed three-dimensional map of the distribution of matter in the universe, and the data of the European Space Telescope Planck clarified the restrictions imposed on the parameters of the CDM.
In July, scientists modeled the possible death of the universe.
Three years earlier, their colleagues had presented new arguments that the observed world would cease to exist in 22 billion years as a result of the Great Divide.
