U.S. thinks about naval blockade of Russia because of oil and gas supplies
The United States may begin a naval blockade of Russia to gain an advantage in the world energy market.
The U.S. authorities are so eager to fight for success in the world hydrocarbon market that they are ready to resort to the naval blockade of Russia, which remains one of the world's main energy suppliers.
U.S. Interior Minister Ryan Zinke told about the possibility of a naval blockade the day before.
Contrary to world practice, the U.S. Department of the Interior does not perform police, but civilian functions, including the implementation of natural resources policy.
Therefore, Zinke's statement came quite within the competence of his department, although it was not deprived of political color.
Speaking at an industrial event in Pittsburgh, Zinke said that thanks to the Navy, the U.S. controls the sea lanes in the Middle East region and can block them if necessary.
According to Zinke, the need may be related to Washington's desire to prevent Russian supplies to the world energy market.
Zinke recalled that Russia still receives the lion's share of its revenues from supplies to the world market of oil and gas.
