The main Macedonian opposition refused to vote in the referendum
Macedonia is holding a referendum on Sunday, 30 September, on an intergovernmental treaty with Greece to rename the Republic of Macedonia.
Citizens are asked to answer one question: "Do you support EU and NATO membership by accepting the agreement between the Republic of Macedonia and the Hellenic Republic?"
Nevertheless, the leader of the leading opposition party "Internal Macedonian Revolutionary Organization - Democratic Party for Macedonian National Unity" (VMRO-DPNE) Christian Mitskoski said that he would not vote in the referendum.
As explained by party spokesman Naum Stoilkovsky, Mitskoski decided to abstain from voting to express his disagreement with the treaty, which he considers "harmful".
According to the spokesman, the current referendum resolves the issue of renaming the country and nothing more, while the strategic goal of the party - to achieve membership in NATO and the EU.
A week ago, Macedonian President Gheorghe Ivanov also refused to participate in the September 30 referendum.
He explained that he chose the name for the country 27 years ago in a referendum on independence.
"A new semi-sovereign state with a new name is being created", Ivanov said.
The agreement on the new official name of the former Yugoslav Republic - the Republic of Northern Macedonia - was signed by the Foreign Ministers of Macedonia and Greece on June 17 this year during a ceremony on the shore of Lake Prespa, which is the border between the two countries.
This treaty should resolve the long-standing dispute over the name of the country, as well as Skopje's path to NATO and the EU, reminds TASS.
